d Rafi was his idol, and he used to dub his singing style on stage shows; for this reason, people often call him modern Rafi. Sonu Nigam completed his schooling at J. D. Tytler School in Delhi and graduated from Delhi University. Singing Career at Early Age When Sonu Nigam was just 4 years old, he used to join stage performances with his father, Agam Kumar Nigam. Slowly he also joined his father at weddings and parties, where they performed together on different songs. Sonu Nigam learnt all his music skills at home from his father. He has grown up by learning every inch of music from him. Sonu's passion for music surpassed every other interest, and later, he pursued this with full focus. He decided to go to Mumbai at 18 with his father to try his luck in the Bollywood music industry. He continued his music training with maestro Ghulam Mustafa Khan and was looking for opportunities. After analyzing his music skills and performances, he considered becoming a playback singer in the Bollywood industry. Sonu Nigam even believed in superstitions, and once he even changed the spelling of his name 'Nigam' to 'Niigaam', he eventually decided to return with the original one. Singing Career Sonu Nigam has recorded devotional, romantic, patriotic, and ghazal songs in various languages like Hindi, Bengali, Gujarati, Nepali, and much more. He has even launched his pop albums and devotional albums in different languages. Nigam's performance is not only limited to India. He has even performed internationally in the countries of Europe, the Middle East, Australia, and Asia. In 2007, Sonu collaborated with 'The Incredibles'. The Incredible comprised Asha Bhosle, Kailash Kher, Kunal Ganjawala, and Sonu Nigam. He also organized solo concerts in Canada and Germany by the name Simply Sonu. He became the first Indian singer to do so. Starting Career: 1990-1999 Sonu Nigam got his first break as a playback singer in 1990 for a song from the movie Janam. Due to some unavoidable circumstances, the movie wasn't released. He even signed the contract with T-Series, but it was rejected because of S. P. Balasubramaniam. Though his contract was turned down, T-Series owner Gulshan Kumar was impressed by his passion and talent and gave him a chance for a song from the hit movie Bewafa Sanam. 'Achha Sila Diya Tune' song gave him great success in Bollywood Industry, and the song was a hit after which people started noticing and appreciating this young talented singer. In 1993 Sonu Nigam released his first album titled 'Rafi Ki Yaadein'; after that, he sang songs for many movies like Khuddar, Hulchul, Shera, Jeet, Dulhe Raja, Veerta and many more. 'O Aasman Wale' Aaja Meri Jaan was his first release. Before this song, he already had sung many. During his initial days, Nigam struggled because he wasn't getting the opportunity for a playback singer. He did advertisements on radio. Sonu's primary source of income came from stage shows where he sang Rafi's songs. Sonu Nigam debuted in Tamil with the song name Vaarayo Thozi. In 1999, Sonu Nigam released his album Deewana under the T-Series label. Career Peak: 2000-2010 The time between 2000 and 2010 was a golden decade of Sonu Nigam's life because he gave many hit songs for which he was nominated in many award shows and won many of them. Suraj Hua Maddham and Panchi Nadiya Pawan Ke were the two most popular songs sung by Sonu Nigam with Alka Yagnik within this period. The title track of the movie Saathiya got Sonu his first Filmfare Award. A. R. Rahman was the composer of the song and lyrics were written by Gulzar. The song that gave Sonu Nigam the biggest success at this time was Kal Ho Naa Ho in 2003. The song was composed by Shankar-Ehsaan-Loy and written by Javed Akhtar. He won two awards for this track. The first was Filmfare Award, and the second was National Film Fare Award for a playback singer in the male category. Sonu Nigam sang four songs with Shreya Ghosal for the movie Parineeta. In 3 Idiots, Sonu Nigam was the leading playback singer. Nigam re-released the album Rafi Ki Yaadein in 2007 in memory of Mohammad Rafi titled Kal Aaj Aur Kal. In 2008 he released Classically Mild and a Punjabi track titled Punjabi Please and Rafi Resurrected. Sonu Nigam even released a song to tribute Michael Jackson after his death. In 2007, Drew Gilpin Faust became the 28th President of Harvard University. There Sonu Nigam sang bhajan during the inauguration programme with Harvard Students. Present Time: 2010-Present time In 2010, Sonu Nigam sang the title track Tees Maar Khan in 54 languages. He also sang the hit song Chori Kiya Re Jiya from the Dabangg. While recording the song Aye Janani, Sonu hit the highest note with open throat effort without using falsetto. In 2010, Sonu Nigam Global Indian Music Academy Awards for the title track All Izz Well. He also won the BIG Star Entertainment Award for best playback singer of the decade. In 2011, Sonu Nigam collaborated with Britney Spears for I Wanna Go and DJ Avicii for Indian Levels. He also wrote and composed the song This Is It. The song was made to tribute Michael Jackson, for which Sonu collaborated with Michael Jackson's brother Jermaine Jackson. Between 2012 and 2015, many of Sonu's songs were redubbed in other singers' voices by music companies because he was fighting for singers' royalties and against the companies' illegal contracts. Sonu said that he wasn't scared of being out because he believed that good sense would prevail in the end. Sonu Nigam also sang the Abhi Mujh Mein Kahin from the movie Agneepath in 2012, which became a huge success and bagged many awards. BIG Star Entertainment Award, 5th Mirchi Music Award, Zee Cine Awards, Times of India Film Awards, 18th and 19th Lions Gold Award and many more. This song also made him a nominee for best playback singer in the male category at Filmfare Awards. Sonu Nigam considers this song one of his best songs to date. In 2013 Sonu composed the title track of the movie Singh Saa